title: 'The View' co-host Whoopi Goldberg addresses links to paedophile Jeffrey Epstein
description: ‘The View’ co-host Whoopi Goldberg has shut down links to paedophile Jeffrey Epstein after her name appeared in the recently released files.  On Tuesday, Goldberg revealed her name appeared in the files and claimed she was addressing it “in the name of transparency”.  Goldberg's name was mentioned in a 2013 email, where an individual says she needs a plane to Monaco and that “John Lennon's charity is paying for it”.  The actress claimed that the email should have said Julian Lennon’s charity, adding that it went on to ask Epstein if he would offer his plane to Goldberg.  Fellow co-host Joy Behar claimed that “anybody can be on this list”, before Goldberg defended herself for appearing in the files.  Well, this is my point. Because I’m telling you, when I tell you people are trying to turn me into, I wasn’t his girlfriend. I wasn’t his friend,” Goldberg said.

title: Prime Minister reaffirms his commitment to Australian safety amid ISIS bride saga
description: Prime Minister Anthony Albanese is again denying the government is assisting so called ISIS brides attempting to return to Australia from Syria.  The prime minister was asked about the issue and reaffirmed his position on keeping Australians safe.  He claimed the government will not provide any assistance to the ISIS brides while also adding he will not breach Australian law.

title: ‘Relevance deprivation syndrome’: Hillary Clinton’s embarrassing meltdown over Trump
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada has commented on Hillary Clinton’s appearance at the Munich Security Conference.  “I can only guess that it’s some kind of relevance deprivation syndrome – she wants to be relevant,” she told Sky News host Rita Panahi.  “She should bow out stage left. Why is she still there?”

title: High-speed rail link expected to cost taxpayers $90 billion
description: A high-speed rail link between Sydney and Newcastle is expected to cost taxpayers up to $90 billion, much higher than original estimates.  Australia's first high-speed rail is on track to be the most expensive individual piece of infrastructure funded by the government.  It will allow trains to run up to 320 kilometres an hour, reducing the current two-hour travel time to one hour.  Labor previously estimated it would cost up to $32 billion to build.

title: Republicans ‘break ranks’ and criticise Trump’s recent tweets
description: Democratic lobbyist Niki Carelli says there have been Republicans “break ranks” against US President Donald Trump.  Ms Carelli told Sky News Australia that there has been a “resolution” in the House of Representatives against President Trump’s tariffs.  “We’ve seen Republicans in both the House and the Senate criticise the president for a recent video that he tweeted.”

title: Annual wage growth is steady at 3.4 per cent
description: Sky News Business Reporter Edward Boyd says there is “no real wage growth” according to the latest statistics from the ABS.  Mr Boyd said wages have come in “below” the level of annual inflation during calendar year 2025.  “So, these are really important numbers; they come out every quarter.”

title: Logan Paul sells rare Pokemon card for record-breaking $16.5 million
description: Sky News host Freya Leach reacts to influencer and WWE superstar Logan Paul selling a Pokemon card for a record $16.5 million USD.  “Logan Paul has sold one of the rarest Pokémon cards in the world,” Ms Leach said.   “He sold this Pokemon card of Pikachu for $16.5 million USD.  “He bought this card for $5.2 million in 2021 … not a bad return on investment.”

title: ‘Embarrassing revelations’: Donald Trump ruthlessly exposes Bill Maher in wild ‘spray’
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi discusses the “embarrassing revelations” from US President Donald Trump’s “spray” at comedian Bill Maher about his “nervous and awkward” behaviour when he visited the White House.  “The President has posted a diatribe mocking Bill Maher, the leftist who he broke bread with last year,” she said.  President Trump said in a post to Truth Social: “It was a total waste of time for me to have this jerk at the White House.  “He came into the famed Oval Office much different than I thought he would be. He was extremely nervous, had zero confidence in himself and, to soothe his nerves, immediately, within seconds, asked for a ‘Vodka Tonic’.  “Fortunately, his television ratings are so low that nobody will learn about his various fake news statements about me. He is no different than Kimmel, Fallon, or Colbert but, I must admit, slightly more talented.”

title: ‘Still in denial’: Jen Psaki attempts to dismiss Epstein files’ ‘damage’ to the left
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi claims the Democrats “are not happy” about the release of the Jeffrey Epstein files because it’s “damaging” the left.  “The Democrats are not happy that despite the media regurgitating their misinformation, the release of these files is damaging the left, including Democrat luminaries like Bill Clinton and billionaires like Reid Hoffman and Bill Gates,” she said.  “But Jen Psaki is still in denial.”

title: Stephen Colbert humbled by CBS after attacking network over pulled interview
description: ‘The Late Show’ host Stephen Colbert has slammed CBS for pulling an interview with Texas Democratic Senate Candidate James Talarico.  Colbert blasted his fellow network after CBS’ lawyers advised the host that the Monday interview with Talarico could not air.  During a segment that did air on Monday, Colbert revealed the exchange he had with the network’s lawyers.  “I was told, in some uncertain terms, that not only could I not have him on, I could not mention me not having him on,” Colbert said.  Colbert’s remarks seemingly follow his unaired interview with the candidate, where he suggested the interview was killed due to the FCC’s “equal time rule”.  The Federal Communications Commission’s “equal time rule” requires broadcast networks and radio stations to give equal airtime to all election candidates.

title: AOC ‘humiliates herself’ again after her ‘incoherent’ attempt at fact-checking Rubio backfires
description: Sky News host Rita Panahi has roasted Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez following her “incoherent attempt” at answering basic questions at the Munich Security Conference.  “She managed to humiliate herself again in Munich with another incoherent attempt to answer basic questions,” she said.  “She attempted to fact-check Marco Rubio’s 100 per cent factual comment about the origins of American cowboys – that didn’t go too well. And she tries to make another profound point here that backfires.  “AOC not only needs to brush up on economics, history, but also geography, it seems, because she has no clue, and those idiots in the crowd clapping along like they just heard some brilliant point.”

title: Iran-US negotiations will not reach ‘sustainable peace deal’
description: Sky News host Andrew Bolt says the Iran-US negotiations will not reach a sustainable peace deal.  “Iran is not going to give up its nuclear weapons,” Mr Bolt said.  “There will not be any real, sustainable peace deal.”

title: One Nation’s popularity to be tested at Farrer by-election
description: Sussan Ley’s resignation is set to trigger a by-election in the seat of Farrer, which will test the growing popularity of One Nation.  Since Farrer’s creation in 1949, only four MPs have represented the seat, all from the Coalition.  Some feel the traditionally safe Coalition seat has been overlooked by Canberra in past elections.

title: Major defence summit in Canberra evacuated as police sweep conference room
description: A major defence summit held in Canberra has been evacuated during a speech by Defence Industry Minister Pat Conroy.  Police stress that the evacuation was purely precautionary, and they are undertaking a search of the room.

title: Ukraine remains ‘steadfast’ against Russia four years after war began
description: Former US Army vice chief of staff General Jack Keane claims Ukraine remains steadfast four years into its war with Russia.  “The Ukrainians have been absolutely steadfast, and people have supported,” Mr Keane told Sky News host Andrew Bolt.  “Here they are four years into this war, and Russia is largely stalemated in terms of its offensive operation.”
